âœ… What is Normalization?
Normalization is a process in database design used to remove redundancy (duplicate data) and avoid anomalies during: INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE

It organizes data into multiple related tables so the database becomes:
âœ” Efficient
âœ” Consistent
âœ” Easy to maintain

Goal:
ğŸ‘‰ Store each fact only once
ğŸ‘‰ Avoid unnecessary duplication
ğŸ‘‰ Make relationships clear

ğŸ¯ Why Normalization is Needed?
Without normalization (in unnormalized form):
| StudentID | StudentName | Course1 | Course2 | Instructor |
| --------- | ----------- | ------- | ------- | ---------- |
| 1         | Suyog       | DBMS    | SQL     | Mehta      |

Problems:
- Redundancy (same instructor repeated for many rows)
- Update anomaly => If instructor name changes, need to update in many places.
- Insert anomaly => Cannot add a course without a student.
- Delete anomaly => Deleting last student deletes course details too.
Normalization fixes this.

ğŸ”¥ Types (Normal Forms)
1ï¸âƒ£ 1NF (First Normal Form)
Rule:
âœ” No repeating groups
âœ” Every column must have atomic (indivisible) values
âœ” Each row must be unique

âŒ Before 1NF:
| Student | Courses   |
| ------- | --------- |
| Suyog   | DBMS, SQL |

âœ” After 1NF:
| Student | Course |
| ------- | ------ |
| Suyog   | DBMS   |
| Suyog   | SQL    |


2ï¸âƒ£ 2NF (Second Normal Form)
Rule:
âœ” Must be in 1NF
âœ” No partial dependency
(A non-key column should not depend on only part of a composite key)

Example:
Table (StudentID, CourseID) â†’ Composite key
| StudentID | CourseID | StudentName |
| --------- | -------- | ----------- |

Problem:
StudentName depends only on StudentID, not CourseID â†’ partial dependency.

âœ” Fix by splitting:

Students Table
| StudentID | StudentName |

Enrollments Table
| StudentID | CourseID |


3ï¸âƒ£ 3NF (Third Normal Form)
Rule:
âœ” Must be in 2NF
âœ” No transitive dependency
(Non-key attribute should not depend on another non-key attribute)

âŒ Example:
| EmpID | EmpName | DeptID | DeptName |
| ----- | ------- | ------ | -------- |

DeptName depends on DeptID â†’ transitive dependency.

âœ” Fix:

Employee
| EmpID | EmpName | DeptID |

Department
| DeptID | DeptName |


4ï¸âƒ£ BCNF (Boyce-Codd Normal Form)
A stronger version of 3NF.

Rule:
âœ” Every determinant must be a candidate key

Used when:
Table has multiple candidate keys
Functional dependencies become complex

ğŸŒŸ Summary Table
| Normal Form | Removes               | Requirement       |
| ----------- | --------------------- | ----------------- |
| **1NF**     | Repeating groups      | Atomic values     |
| **2NF**     | Partial dependency    | Must be in 1NF    |
| **3NF**     | Transitive dependency | Must be in 2NF    |
| **BCNF**    | Advanced anomalies    | Stronger than 3NF |


ğŸ“˜ Real Example of Full Normalization
Student Course Table (Unnormalized)
| StudentID | StudentName | Course | Instructor |
| --------- | ----------- | ------ | ---------- |

After Normalization:
Students
| StudentID | StudentName |

Courses
| CourseID | CourseName | Instructor |

StudentCourse
| StudentID | CourseID |

ğŸ¯ Benefits of Normalization
âœ” Eliminates duplicate data
âœ” Avoids update/insert/delete anomalies
âœ” Makes database efficient
âœ” Improves data consistency
âœ” Saves storage

ğŸ“Œ Interview Answer (Short Version)
Normalization is a database design technique used to remove redundancy and avoid anomalies by organizing data into multiple related tables. 
It follows several normal forms like 1NF, 2NF, 3NF, and BCNF. Each form reduces a specific type of redundancy (repeating groups, partial dependency, transitive dependency).



