âœ… What Are ACID Properties?
ACID is a set of 4 properties that ensure a database transaction is reliable, consistent, and safe, even if failures happen.

A transaction = a group of SQL operations executed together
(e.g., money transfer, booking ticket, order placement)

ğŸ‘‰ ACID ensures that even if power fails, network breaks, system crashes, data remains safe.

ğŸ”¥ ACID = Atomicity + Consistency + Isolation + Durability

1ï¸âƒ£ Atomicity â†’ â€œAll or Nothingâ€
A transaction must either:
âœ” complete fully
âŒ or not happen at all

There is no partial execution.

ğŸ¦ Example (Money Transfer)
Transfer â‚¹500 from A â†’ B
Two operations happen: 1) Deduct 500 from A, 2) Add 500 to B

If the system crashes after step 1 â†’
Step 2 must NOT happen.

Either:
âœ” both succeed
âŒ or both fail

This is Atomicity.



2ï¸âƒ£ Consistency â†’ â€œValid Data Before & After Transactionâ€
After every transaction, the database must remain valid according to rules (constraints).

Examples:
No negative bank balance (if rule says so)
Age cannot be negative
Foreign key constraints must match

Example:
If total money in bank A+B = â‚¹5000
â†’ after transaction, total must still be â‚¹5000

No rules should break.



3ï¸âƒ£ Isolation â†’ â€œTransactions do not interfereâ€
If multiple transactions run at the same time,
each transaction should behave as if it's the only one running.

ğŸ›’ Example:
Two users buying the last item on Amazon:
User 1 adds to cart
User 2 adds to cart

Isolation ensures:
âœ” only ONE will successfully purchase
âŒ both cannot buy the last item

Prevents issues like:
Dirty reads
Lost updates
Phantom reads


4ï¸âƒ£ Durability â†’ â€œOnce committed, data is safe foreverâ€
After a transaction is committed:
âœ” it must survive system crashes, power failure, or reboot
âœ” DB writes it to disk / logs permanently

Example:
If you send money and you get â€œTransaction Successfulâ€:
Even if power goes OFF the next secondâ€¦

âœ” the money is transferred
âŒ it will NOT roll back

Because DB has stored it permanently.


â­ Summary Table
| ACID Property   | Meaning                              | Real-Life Example                       |
| --------------- | ------------------------------------ | --------------------------------------- |
| **Atomicity**   | All or nothing                       | Money transfer (both steps must happen) |
| **Consistency** | Data remains valid                   | No negative balance                     |
| **Isolation**   | No interference between transactions | Multiple users buying same product      |
| **Durability**  | Save permanently                     | Transaction stays even after crash      |

ğŸ“Œ Interview Answer (Short)
ACID properties are a set of rules that ensure reliable transaction processing in a database.
They include:
Atomicity â€“ all operations in a transaction succeed or fail together
Consistency â€“ database must remain valid after the transaction
Isolation â€“ concurrent transactions do not affect each other
Durability â€“ once committed, data is permanently saved


